==Records==
{{main|Derry City F.C. records}}
[[Image:Dcfcstandings.PNG|thumb|right|220px|A graphical representation of Derry City's historical standings in the [[Irish League]] and [[League of Ireland]]. <small>(Enlarge to study.)</small>]]
Current [[player-manager]], [[Peter Hutton (footballer)|Peter Hutton]], holds the club record for matches played in [[League of Ireland]] football with 570 competitive appearances since the 1990&ndash;91 season.<ref>Dunleavy, Brian. [http://derrycityfc.net/players/current/phutton.php Player Profiles - Peter Hutton]. ''CityWeb'', 2007. Retrieved on [[2007-05-04]].</ref> [[Paul Curran (footballer)|Paul Curran]] has made the second highest number of appearances for the club in the League of Ireland with 518, followed by [[Sean Hargan]] with 403 since 1995.<ref><span style="font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: bold; color:#555;">i)</span> Dunleavy, Brian ([[2006-11-17]]). "They must be enjoying the experience!", ''CityView'', vol. 22, no. 27, p. 18.<br>'''<font color="White">^</font>''' <span style="font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: bold; color:#555;">ii)</span> As of [[2 June]], [[2007]].</ref>

The club's all-time highest goal-scorer is [[Jimmy Kelly]] with 363 goals between 1930 and 1951.<ref>[http://nifootball.blogspot.com/2007/01/jimmy-kelly.html Jimmy Kelly]. ''Northern Ireland's Footballing Greats'', [[2007-01-20]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-04]].</ref> Since the entry of the club into [[League of Ireland]] football, [[Liam Coyle]] is Derry's top scorer with 112 goals after 390 competitive appearances for the club between 1988 and 2003.<ref>Kelly, David. "[http://www.unison.ie/irish_independent/stories.php3?ca=94&si=1111677&issue_id=10329 Genius finally hangs up his boots]", ''Irish Independent'', [[2004-01-21]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-04]]. <small>(Registration required.)</small></ref> Derry's first ever scorer was [[Peter Burke (footballer)|Peter Burke]] at home to [[Glentoran]] on [[22 August]], [[1929]] as the club lost 2&ndash;1.<ref name=Firsts>"[http://derrycityfc.net/club/folklore/firsts.php They were the First...]", ''CityWeb'', 2007. Retrieved on [[2007-05-04]].</ref> Two days later, [[Sammy Curran]] had the honour of scoring Derry's first [[hat-trick]], as the club came back from 5&ndash;1 down away to [[Portadown FC|Portadown]], only to lose 6&ndash;5 to a late goal.<ref name=Firsts/> [[Barry McCreadie]] was Derry's first scorer in the [[League of Ireland]] as he scored during a 3&ndash;1 home win over [[Home Farm]] on [[8 September]], [[1985]].<ref name=Firsts/> Derry's first hat-trick in the League of Ireland was scored by [[Kevin Mahon]] away to [[Finn Harps]] on [[15 December]], [[1985]].<ref name=Firsts/> A number of capped internationals have also played for Derry.

Derry's record League of Ireland defeat was to [[Longford Town FC|Longford Town]] in January, 1986 &mdash; the score was 5&ndash;1.<ref name=GenInfo/> The club's record League of Ireland win was 9&ndash;1 against [[Galway United]] in October, 1986.<ref name=GenInfo/> The club has never been relegated in either the [[Irish League]] or the League of Ireland.<ref name=FIFAcom/> Derry are one of only two League of Ireland teams to have completed a [[The Treble|treble]]. Derry's 5&ndash;1 away win against [[Gretna FC|Gretna]] at [[Fir Park]], [[Motherwell]] in the 2006&ndash;07 [[UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup's]] Second Qualifying Round is the largest away winning margin for any [[League of Ireland]] team in European competition. Derry played a record number of 54 games in the whole [[Football League of Ireland 2006 season|2006 season]], including all competitions. Previously, the record had been the 49 games played in all competitions during the treble-winning 1988-89 season.<ref> Wilson (2007), p. 50.</ref>

[[The Brandywell|The Brandywell's]] record attendance in the League of Ireland system is 9,800 people who attended an [[FAI Cup]] Second Round tie between Derry and [[Finn Harps]] on [[23 February]], [[1986]].<ref name=Whatsthescore/> In the [[Irish League]], a crowd of 12,000 attended the 1929&ndash;30 season home game against [[Linfield F.C.|Linfield]].<ref> Mahon (1998), p. 63.</ref>

==Supporters==
{{main|Traditions of Derry City F.C.}}
[[Image:DCFCPSG.jpg|thumb|220px|Derry City's fans in the [[Parc des Princes]], [[Paris]] on [[28 September]], 2006.]]
By Irish standards, Derry City have a relatively large and loyal fan-base. The club were considered among the strongest and best-supported teams in the [[Irish League]],<ref name=FIFAcom>"[http://www.fifa.com/en/mens/index/0,2527,122678,00.html?articleid=122678 Derry City dream on in Paris]", ''FIFA.com'', [[2006-09-27]]. Retrieved on [[2007-04-30]].</ref> and upon the club's entry into the [[Football League of Ireland|League of Ireland]] in 1985, crowds of nearly 10,000 attended to the [[Brandywell]] for the return of matches.<ref name=Collins/> Derry's average home attendance of 3,127 was the highest of any team for the 2006 season.<ref>[http://foot.ie/forums/archive/index.php/t-48537.html eircom League AGM - Acting Director's Report]. ''Foot.ie'', [[2006-12-10]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-05]].</ref> The highest attendance was the last-night-of-the-season meeting between Derry and [[Cork City F.C.|Cork City]] at the [[Brandywell]] on Friday [[17 November]] when 6,080 watched Derry win 1&ndash;0.<ref>"[http://www.tribune.ie/2006/12/10/80154.html Derry's game with Cork best attended]", ''Sunday Tribune'', [[2006-12-10]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-04]].</ref> Domestically, Derry's supporters travel to away games in "bus-loads".<ref name=EdMahon/> They gave large support in the club's 2006 [[UEFA Cup]] run &mdash; around 3,000 travelled to [[Motherwell]] and "maintained a wall of sound" as Derry beat [[Gretna F.C.|Gretna]] 5&ndash;1 in [[Fir Park]],<ref>Halliday, Stephen. "[http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/sport.cfm?id=1167012006 Slack Gretna given cruel lesson by five-star Derry]", ''The Scotsman'', [[2006-08-11]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-09]].</ref><ref>"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/4782159.stm Kenny elated after Derry triumph]", ''BBC Sport Online'', [[2006-08-10]]. Retrieved on [[2007-04-30]].</ref> and over 2,000 went to [[Paris]] to see Derry play [[Paris Saint-Germain]] in the [[Parc des Princes]].<ref>{{fr icon}} [http://psg-fans-gretz.skyrock.com/ Paris SG - Derry City / Coupe de l'UEFA 2006/2007]. ''psg-fans-gretz, SkyRock'', [[2007-03-01]]. Retrieved on [[2007-04-30]].</ref> During the home legs, ticketless fans desperate to see the games watched from a distance while standing on the high vantage point overlooking the Brandywell offered by the City Cemetery in [[Creggan, Derry|Creggan]] and parked hired [[double-decker]] buses outside the stadium to help them see over the ground's perimeter.<ref>Carton, Donna. "[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4161/is_20060903/ai_n16710323 Bus is just the ticket for fans]", ''Sunday Mirror'', [[2006-09-03]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-11]].</ref><ref>"[http://www.unison.ie/irish_independent/stories.php3?ca=94&si=1677035&issue_id=14561 Derry hordes cheer heroes into uncharted territory]", ''Irish Independent'', [[2006-08-25]]. Retrieved on [[2007-05-11]]. <small>(Registration required.)</small></ref>

The club is known for its community spirit and the supporters have played a pivotal role in the survival and successes of the club. When debts brought Derry close to extinction in the 2000&ndash;01 season, the local community responded en masse to help save the club. During the club's successful 2006 season, club captain, [[Peter Hutton (footballer)|Peter Hutton]] said:
{{blockquote|Nobody owns Derry City F.C. apart from the people of Derry. Five or six years ago the club was on its knees, on the verge of going out of business. There was no sugar-daddy, no millionaire, no [[Roman Abramovich]] to save the club. It was the people and the city who saved the club. People, fans, ordinary people; they went out and banged on doors to collect money, they went around pubs with collection buckets, they did what they could to keep the club alive. Derry is a close-knit place, a small community, they care about their club and that's why we still have a club. And every bit of success we may get this season is down to them.<ref>Fitzmaurice, Aidan. "[http://www.uefa.com/magazine/news/kind=134217728/newsid=457048.html Derry dare to dream]", ''[[UEFA|UEFA.com]]'', [[2006-09-15]]. Retrieved on [[2007-04-30]].</ref>}}
[[Image:No1527r.jpg|thumb|right|220px|A [[Northern Irish murals|mural]] in [[Shantallow]], [[Derry]] depicts Derry City's association with Derry's [[Irish nationalist|nationalist]] community. Derry City's crest can be seen in the bottom left, next to a large [[Celtic FC|Celtic]] crest, along with an [[Irish tricolour]], a [[Derry GAA]] flag and a [[shamrock]] &mdash; all symbols revered by various elements of the nationalist community.<ref>The mural, dominated by the [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] crest, demonstrates the trend exhibited by the majority of Irish football fans who primarily support clubs from [[Scottish Premier League|Scotland]] or [[FA Premier League|England]], ahead of teams from their own national league. This has had a detrimental effect on the development of Irish football. For further information on this, see: {{cite book |
 author=Whelan, Daire |
 title=Who Stole Our Game?: The Fall and Fall of Irish Soccer |
 publisher=Gill & Macmillan |
 year=2006 |
 pages= |
 id=ISBN 9780717140046 }}</ref>]]
Likewise, former [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]] leader and [[Nobel Peace Prize]] winner [[John Hume]] [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]], who is the club's current president,<ref>[http://www.derrycityfc.net/club/general.php Derry City Football Club - General Information]. ''CityWeb'', 2007. Retrieved on [[2007-04-30]].</ref> stated in 1998 of the club's relationship with the community:
{{blockquote|Derry City F.C. has been the lynchpin in the life of the community in Derry since its foundation in 1928. Throughout the club's history, the Candystripes have provided a sporting outlet for young people and older supporters alike. The history of the club is intertwined with that of its city. It has seen struggle and marginalisation turn to renewal and success. The pride people have in this club reflects the pride we hold in our city. Derry City players and supporters alike are superb ambassadors for the city. Today, the club, like the city, looks to the future with great hope. For all its successes, Derry City would be nothing without the people of the city.<ref>Mahon (1998). "Foreword" by [[John Hume|Hume, John]], p. 2.</ref>}}

Support for the club is quite dependent on geography and crosses social boundaries. Fans come from both [[working class]] areas, such as the Brandywell area and [[Bogside]], and more affluent regions of the city, like [[Culmore]]. The Cityside is seen as the traditional base of the club, especially the Brandywell area, although the [[Waterside, Derry|Waterside]] is also home to a smaller number of supporters.<ref name=Cronin/> The club are supported mainly by Derry's [[Irish nationalist|nationalist]] community. The connection is rooted mainly in [[geography]], as well as [[social]], [[cultural]] and [[historical]] circumstances, as opposed to the club or its fans pushing towards the creation of a certain identity.<ref name=Cronin/> The club has a small minority of supporters of a [[Protestant]] upbringing. The city's Protestant community is largely apathetic, though some [[Unionism (Ireland)|unionists]] and [[Ulster loyalism|loyalists]] damn the club as a symbol of Catholicism and nationalism.<ref name=Cronin/><ref>For a more in-depth analysis and study of [[Ethnicity and football|sectarian divisions and the politico-religious alignment of certain communities of fans to certain clubs]] within domestic Irish (especially Northern Irish) football, see: {{cite book |
 author=Cronin, Mike |
 title=Sport and Nationalism in Ireland: Gaelic Games, Soccer and Irish Identity Since 1884 |
 publisher=Four Courts Press |
 year=1999 |
 pages= |
 id=ISBN 978-1851824564 }}; {{cite book |
 author=Cronin, Mike & Mayall, David |
 title=Sporting Nationalisms: Identity, Ethnicity, Immigration, and Assimilation |
 publisher=Routledge |
 year=1998 |
 pages= |
 id=ISBN 978-0714644493 }}; {{cite book |
 author=Dunn, Seamus |
 title=Facets of the Conflict in Northern Ireland |
