 title=Off the Ball |
 publisher=Longwood |
 year=1986 |
 pages="Observe the Sons of Ulster: Football and Politics in Northern Ireland" by Bairner, Alan & Sugden, John, pp. 146&ndash;157 |
 id=ISBN 9780745301228 }}</ref> Joining the [[Republic of Ireland|Republic of Ireland's]] league augmented the perception and, on occasion, Protestant [[hooligans]] have thrown missiles at Derry's supporter buses as they journeyed to or returned from games across the border.<ref>{{cite book |
 author=Sugden, John & Bairner, Alan |
 title=Sport, Sectarianism and Society in a Divided Ireland |
 publisher=Leicester University Press |
 year=1995 |
 pages=p. 87 |
 id=ISBN 978-0718500184 }}</ref> Minor nationalist elements within the Derry City support-base see football as a means of reinforcing [[sectarianism|sectarian]] divides.<ref name=Cronin/>  

With the city being a focal point of culture and activity serving the north-west region of [[Ireland]], support stretches beyond the urban border and into the surrounding [[County Londonderry|county]]; [[Limavady]], [[Strabane]] in nearby [[County Tyrone]]<ref>[http://www.strabanedc.org.uk/council/minutes/item.php?q=599&sr=30&month=04&year=2004&search_keyword= Minutes of the Special Meeting of Council]. Strabane District Council press release, [[2006-10-03]]. Retrieved on [[2007-04-23]].</ref> and areas of bordering [[County Donegal]] contain support.<ref>[http://www.derrycityfc.net/icandy/ Episode 3]. ''iCandy'', 2006-05. Retrieved on [[2007-04-30]].</ref> The club has numerous supporter clubs, along with [[Ultras|ultra fans]], and support beyond Ireland &mdash; mainly emigrated city natives. ''Derry City Chat'' is a discussion website run by fans. Derry's fans share a [[Northwest Derby|rivalry]] with the supporters of [[Finn Harps]] and sing the [[Undertones|Undertones']] ''[[Teenage Kicks]]'' as a terrace anthem.<ref name=Collins/>

